Dynamic structures
form a chain of data points => effective way to manage and manipulate information
Key use: adding, removing, traversing through elements

A linkedList is fundamentally made up of a set of nodes.
Node = data(value)+reference(pointer)
Types: singly linked list and doubly linked list

Advantage: dynamic so easier to add and remove elements even in the middle of list,without having to move any other elements
Disadvantage: direct retrieval of an element by index---> must traverse list from beginning to end to get desired point, time complexity: O(n)

1. Dynamic Size: grow/shrink as needed without requiring additional memory/space 
2. Efficient Insertion and deletions: changing node references
3. Memory Efficiency: memory alloted for every node separately---> no memory fragmentation

java.util.LinkedList : doubly linkedList.
Implements : List and Deque
        LinkedList<String> l = new LinkedList<String>();

Add/modify: add(), addFirst(), addLast()
Access: get(int index), getFirst(), getLast()
Remove: remove(), removeFirst(), removeLast()

